10
00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:24.880
First; Who is the audience.

11
00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:30.680
We need to understand who will be interacting with the dashboard and the user’s relative knowledge in this area.

12
00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:30.680


13
00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:30.680


14
00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:30.680


15
00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:32.800
Second; What do they need?

16
00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:35.800
For this, we need to understand the goal of those using our

17
00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:40.440
dashboard or more importantly, what they will using the dashboard for.

18
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:40.440


19
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:40.440


20
00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:40.480


21
00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:42.920
Finally; How can a dashboard help.

22
00:00:42.920 --> 00:00:46.960
The dashboard needs to be more than just exciting visuals; it needs to provide

23
00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:51.640
insights relevant to an audience member to help them act in a particular manner.

24
00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:51.640


25
00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:51.640


26
00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:55.160
Let's dive into the who, what, and how for this dashboard.

27
00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:55.160


28
00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:55.160


29
00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.080
The recruiters at DataSearch are the Who.

30
00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:01.160
They are very familiar with this field, so it is okay to assume that they

31
00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:05.000
will understand all of the previous metrics we have utilized and uncovered.

32
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:05.600


33
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:05.600


34
00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:11.800
For the “What”, the recruiter’s goal is to connect those looking for roles with employers that match.

35
00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:15.760
The easier we can identify potential opportune areas for qualified

36
00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:19.520
candidates, the easier it will be for a recruiter to accomplish their job.

37
00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:19.520


38
00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:20.280


39
00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:21.600
Finally, the “How”.

40
00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:26.000
We need to transform the insights of this data into a useable form for the recruiters.

41
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.800
This will be the primary focus area as we build out this dashboard.

42
00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:30.800


43
00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:30.800


44
00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:32.520
When designing our dashboard, it’s

45
00:01:32.520 --> 00:01:37.200
essential to think of three major questions when creating the overall layout for a dashboard.

46
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:38.000


47
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:38.000


48
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.960
First, what significant visualizations do we want to include on this dashboard?

49
00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:48.320
We don’t want to have too many as this would be distracting; instead, we only wish to use the most valuable visuals.

50
00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:48.320


51
00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:48.320


52
00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:49.040


53
00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:49.040


54
00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:53.400
Next, we need to ensure the most intuitive visuals are used for these visuals.

55
00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.040
If we are using a more complex visual, does our audience

56
00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:01.120
understand this visual, or do we have to take the time to explain it to them.

57
00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:01.120


58
00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:01.120


59
00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:06.480
Finally, we need to use sizing, positioning, & coloring to draw

60
00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:09.800
our users attention to key insights that will help solve their problem.

61
00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:09.800


62
00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:10.640


63
00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:15.120
When diving into the design of a dashboard, it’s essential to think of aspects

64
00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:15.920
such as:

65
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:15.920


66
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:15.960


67
00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:19.600
- Using the least amount of visuals to avoid overwhelming your audience.

68
00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:19.600


69
00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:24.480
- Giving context behind whether a number is good or bad by providing reference values.

70
00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:25.040


71
00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:30.360
- Using labels, via axes and titles, to avoid confusion about visuals provided.

72
00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:30.960


73
00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:35.320
- Finally, making the dashboard interactive so users can explore the data.

74
00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:35.320


75
00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:35.320


76
00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:38.960
Based on our previous research, it makes sense to break up

77
00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:44.080
the dashboard into three separate areas: Job, Skills, and Company.

78
00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:47.920
The dashboard will need to be designed in a way that recruiters at

79
00:02:47.920 --> 00:02:52.560
DataSearch can dive deeper into one of these topic areas based on their needs.

80
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:52.560


81
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:52.560


82
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:52.560


83
00:02:52.560 --> 00:02:57.200
For all the dashboards we’ll be designing it in a consistent manner, placing

84
00:02:57.200 --> 00:03:02.120
corresponding key metrics at the top of the dashboard, along with slicers on the left-hand side.

85
00:03:02.120 --> 00:03:05.040
For the visuals in the center of the dashboards, we will be

86
00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.480
taking use of the previously designed visuals that we have made.

87
00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:08.480


88
00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:08.480


89
00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:12.080
When we are done, we’ll make a home page for the dashboard that has

90
00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:17.000
click-able icons for users to navigate to the area they would like to investigate further.

91
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:17.000


92
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:17.000


93
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.120
Alright, let's dive in with building these dashboards!

